00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
Feature disappears.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:43.000
You create a feature.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:44.000
You merge it back into main.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:45.000
You create a feature.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:46.000
You merge it back into main.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
It's called the GitHub workflow, right?

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
You know, it's nice and simple.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:51.000
It's not that hard.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
There's nothing particularly fancy.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
It just sort of works.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
And so what I would suggest here is, you know, well, first of all, you should protect your main branch, right?

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.000
So protecting your main branch just means you can't push to it, right?

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
You know, you have to go through this branching.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And people always sit here and nod, but when it comes down to actually locking down the main branch, they don't like that.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:13.000
But that's a side problem.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.000
And then have some basic continuous integration, right?

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.000
So continuous integration is when you push something up to Git, so GitHub or GitLab,

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
and a little computer in the sky does some work for you, right?

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So it sort of chugs away.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And if you pass all its tests, you hear nothing.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And if you don't pass, it sends you nasty messages saying you failed.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
And the sort of test could be, does your Shiny app run?

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
I'm not talking about 100-unit tests.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
I'm just saying, does it run?

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
If you run run app, will it actually just run the app, right?

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
Nothing particularly fancy.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
Can you build your package?

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Again, not going through CRAN, but just...

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
If anyone's got a CI for that, that'd be good.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
But does your package just sort of build?

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
Right, it's as simple as that.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
Does your quarter doc compile?

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
Right, so something relatively simple, relatively straightforward,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
that just takes that little bit of pain and suffering away.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
So that's what I'd say to start.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
So here, a little Downton Abbey guy.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Well, he's now tries to push to main, and he gets a very sad face.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:18.000
So he's not very happy now.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
But he can make a little dev branch.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
So here I'm pretending it's a little Shiny app.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So I've made a little drop-down menu.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.000
I push to a branch.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And then a CI passes.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.000
That's good.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
It can get merged into main.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And when you're doing this in GitHub and GitLab,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:37.000
you can do things like if the CI passes,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
it automatically gets merged.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
Right, you can sort of do that sort of stuff.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.000
So you don't have to sort of go to GitHub

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
and then start clicking lots of buttons,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:45.000
because if you're clicking lots of buttons,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
you're probably doing it wrong.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
But you can set it up so you can actually push from the command line.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:51.000
It creates that branch.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:52.000
It runs a CI.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
If the CI passes, it automatically merges.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And everything just disappears.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So you're sort of still at that nice, simple step.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
But you've got that safety net of not shooting yourself

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
and then digging a big hole for yourself

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:04.000
and then throwing it in head first.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
You're a bit more safe.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.000
So let's suppose we're getting a bit more important.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So we've got a larger team.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
So you might have two, three, four, five people.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
So there's more than one developer.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
And we're wanting to keep track of who owns what.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And we're also, so I used to work in academia.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
And I used to work with a professor writing a paper.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And we used to use Git.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And his idea of using Git, he would phone me and say, right,

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
I'm about to do some commits.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
And then he would hang up the phone, and he would commit.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
He was more senior to me, so you just have to agree.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
He was like, yes, OK.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.000
So that was our Git workflow, was a phone call.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Not recommending that workflow in case anyone's not paying attention.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Don't do the phoning part.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Whatever works.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
So keeping track of who owns what.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
So there's a code owner file.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
This is a really simple idea.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And I think lots of your Git repos should have it.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
So it's a very simple text file.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
GitHub and GitLab understand this natively.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
So that means that GitHub actually understands what this file does

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
and means and all that sort of thing.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
You basically create a little file called .github slash code owners.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
Just Google it.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
And it looks something like this.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
So star just means the group notes admin,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
so that would be a group of users, can do what they want.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
They can merge, join, and all that sort of stuff.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And this person, Amy, has also got those superpowers.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Then we've got another directory.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
So website might be a directory inside my Git repo.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
And website admins and Tim is only allowed to change that website,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
but they're not allowed to change other stuff.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
There's a few more options, but keep it simple.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And this is great because now we can start locking down this workflow.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And also, if you're working in a team,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:51.000
so we deal a lot with governments and those sorts of organizations

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
where people move around teams.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
Because this is a file, it's a programmatic file,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
you can now write queries such as,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
what Git repos is Tim involved in?

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So Tim is moving from organization A to over here.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
So before Tim leaves, we can say,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Tim, what repos are you involved in?

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And we've now got a programmatic way of pulling that information out.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
And then we can rearrange responsibilities.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
And that's nice.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And so essentially, we've got exactly the same workflow,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
except we've got code owners who are people doing the merging part.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Not that hard, quite simple.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Next one, so we're moving along this line.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Scheduled CI.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
So you've got your CI up and running.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So scheduled CI, hopefully you can figure this part out.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
It's a CI that's scheduled.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:42.000
So what we do is we've got a whole bunch of internal R packages,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
probably like most of the people here.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
And they're built once a month.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
It's on the 10th, and I've got them scheduled to run

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
from sometime between midnight and 8 o'clock.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
So when things break, you just get all these random messages

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
through this period of eight hours.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And so we've got internal R packages.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Any errors are sent to a Slack channel.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:01.000
So everything passes.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
So some months, not a problem.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
Other months, things start to fail.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So in the 10th of every month, we get all these checks.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
And then crucially, we assign someone at Jumping Rivers to fix that.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
We give them actual time in their workload.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
We say three hours a month, you've got to fix anything that comes up.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
Some months, not a problem.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
They don't have anything, so don't know what to do.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:26.000
Go to the pub or something.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Other months, it's a bit more painful.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
But there's that time where things are just kept routine.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
Also, a useful thing is when something breaks,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
we then have to think about, do we care about this?

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Or should we just get rid of this stuff?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
It's very good for doing legacy software.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
If something breaks, and you actually have to fix a silly thing,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
you think a lot more carefully of, does anyone actually use it?

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
Do I really care about this?

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Or could I just archive it?

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:54.000
So that's also just a nice way.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Especially, I think, in many organizations,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
it's quite easy to create this stuff.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
And you look a year back, and you've just got stuff everywhere.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
It keeps you honest.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Right.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.000
Next thing.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:06.000
So we're moving on.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Continuous deployment.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
That tends to go along with continuous integration.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So here, what I'm wanting is I've created a new feature.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
And when I create that new feature and push that to Git,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:19.000
I want something deployed without me having to press buttons.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
I want magic to happen.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:22.000
Okay?

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
So what I'm meaning here is we've got the setup as before.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
Code owner, can't push to main.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:33.000
When I push this new drop-down menu to my app,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:39.000
I automatically launch that Shiny app with that new feature.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:40.000
So I'm pushing to the branch.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
I've created this branch.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And the Shiny app is automatically created for me.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And then that means that my wonderful code owner can then go in,

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.000
can review the code, and can also start clicking on things in the Shiny app.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
You're taking that little bit of effort away from them.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:00.000
And then if everything passes, the code owner is happy, it passes the CI,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
then it would automatically deploy onto the production server.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.000
So no one is having to press deploy, go, move forward.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
And then when I've merged that,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:14.000
the dev app would just sort of magically disappear without anyone having to worry about it.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
This part is starting to take a bit more infrastructure.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
This part is starting to take a bit more maintenance.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
Doing a code owner's file is dead easy.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
It's ten minutes of Googling, five minutes of writing.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
This stuff you're having to think about,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
where you're launching a Shiny app, for example,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
it's going to connect or it's going to wherever you want.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
And then you have to try and destroy it when that branch is then merged.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And so it does get a little bit more tricky.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
But it's a really nice workflow.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
And that's what we do internally.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.000
So it works really well.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
The last part,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and I'm just going to just sort of lump this into sort of pedantic CI.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And this is just sort of wherever you want to go.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
So,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.000
full honesty,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
I did this one first seven years ago and really annoyed the whole company.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.000
But that's a side problem.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
So a news file,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
you can have a little CI job that checks as a news file formatted properly.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:09.000
Does it have,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
has it been updated?

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
So one of our CI jobs is whenever you update the package,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
it checks that the package version has been updated.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
So you've made a change to the package.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.000
So the version must be updated.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
Otherwise installed packages just breaks.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.000
So it checks that.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And it goes,

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:25.000


00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:26.000
if you've updated the version number,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
have you updated the news file?

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:29.000
Because it's really easy to forget this stuff.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
It's a little CI job that just checks this.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.000
So it checks as a description tidy as well.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
It does other things like our file names,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
lowercase.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
You could,

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
we could do some stuff and commit messages,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.000
talk about later.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:45.000
But the world's your oyster,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.000
right?

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
You could start thinking about,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:49.000
actually,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
we've got 50% unit test coverage.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:52.000
If you make any changes,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
it must be at least 50% or greater unit test.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
You're not allowed to degrade that experience.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So you can start adding on all these hoops to go through.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:07.000
This stuff here starts to make it hard to onboard team members onto.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:08.000
All right?

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.000
So all this stuff will say,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.000
well,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:14.000
you can't just get someone in jumping to start doing commits because

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
you've got all this stuff to sort of make things proper.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
But it depends where you are in that line.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:19.000
All right?

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:20.000
You know,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:21.000
if you're making software,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
the effort breaks and lots of people are going to be upset,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:24.000
then,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:25.000
well,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.000
that's what you have to do.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:27.000
You don't want to mistake.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:28.000
So,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.000
I mean,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:30.000
it's where you are in that line.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Something that,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.000
you know,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:33.000
so commit lint,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.000
that's not an R package,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:35.000
by the way.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:36.000
So if you Google it,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:37.000
it's a,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:38.000
it's an additional sort of add on.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.000
Essentially,

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:40.000
whenever you do a commit,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.000
it checks your commit message.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
It follows particular standards.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:44.000
Right?

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
So the first part,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
for example,

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.000
we have a bunch of keywords.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:48.000
So it might be chore,

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:49.000
fix,

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:50.000
feature,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:51.000
CI,

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:52.000
docs,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:53.000
you know,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.000
those sorts of words.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:55.000
If you do anything other than those words,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
you'll get a little shifty message.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
They don't do some stuff in the right hand side.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
So does it start with a capital letter?

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Is it too long?

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:03.000
Is it too short?

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:04.000
So again,

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:05.000
it does that.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.000
This can be really annoying,

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.000
right?

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.000
This works well when you've got this mythical place,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:12.000
which I always live in,

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
where your first commit just works.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Because your first commit you do,

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:17.000
I am feature,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.000
you know,

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:19.000
adding a new dev,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.000
a new dropdown menu.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
But then you've got another 15 commits after that

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
in order to fix a thing that didn't quite work.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
And so I tend to then write,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:27.000
fix,

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:28.000
bump,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.000
fix,

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:30.000
bump,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:31.000
and then you're into rebasing and all that sort of stuff.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So it can be really annoying,

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
but it can also be useful.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
I really do mean it can be really annoying.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:37.000
Right.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:38.000
So just to summarize,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
so if you're at the far left,

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:41.000
and it's only you,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:42.000
who cares?

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.000
Right.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Basically,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.000
you know,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:46.000
use something simple,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:47.000
get stuff done.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:48.000
Right.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.000
But then as you sort of make your way along,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:52.000
you know,

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:53.000
people are actually using your software,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
and that could be future you in a year's time.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:56.000
Right.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.000
I hate past me.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.000
He's a complete,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.000
right?

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.000
Then you want to start thinking about protecting main,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:04.000
adding in CI,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
thinking about code owners,

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:07.000
if there's more than one person,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
thinking about scheduled CI.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Scheduled CI,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.000
again,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:11.000
five-minute job to set up.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
Right.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:13.000
You can stick in a slack hook,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.000
or stick in an email.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.000
Not that hard.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:16.000
You know,

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.000
once you've got that,

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:18.000
quite easy.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
Not so much fun when you get 15 slack messages,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:21.000
telling you all your packages are broken,

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:22.000
but side point.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Continuous deployment,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
absolutely wonderful,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
but that's not a five-minute job.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.000
That also,

